english:
  title: Memorial Requesting Release from High Office
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The moon waxes full only to wane. All things shun the peril of excess. The sun sets and rests; man cannot labor eternal. How much more so when one presumes upon favor and lingers overlong—even repentance comes too late. I dare lay bare my sincere heart and humbly petition to be freed from these heavy burdens.

    Reflecting upon my fortune: I, a mere vessel of mediocre talents, rose early to prominence and office. From the reign of the Illustrious Ancestor to this Sacred Age, I have served three sovereigns. From the Hall of Ministers to the seat of Chancellor, more than a decade has passed. Yet I have achieved nothing worthy of record, only drawn stipends in abundance. Even in ordinary times, I trembled at my inadequacy; how much more now, when my frail form weakens under countless afflictions. My eyes dim and blur—I can scarce distinguish what lies before them. My body withers thin—it cannot bear the weight of my robes. How can I remain, when this is my state? Though the ruler above possesses boundless compassion, the Chancellor's seat is no position for one to idle away.

    I humbly beseech Your Majesty: extend your pity and tender mercy upon this broken and withered thing. Grant me your imperial command to retire and rest. Let me drink of the harmonious essence of this golden age in my remaining years, nourishing what life remains. Though I withdraw from court, let my loyalty hang like scarlet thread upon the palace gate—a bond no single day shall sever.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a formal resignation memorial (표, pyo) addressed to the king, written in the traditional style of official court documents.
